About

Noomi Rapace is a 44 year old Swedish Actress. Born Hilda Noomi Norén on 28th December, 1979 in Hudiksvall, Hälsingland, Gävleborg County, Sweden, she is famous for her roles as Lucinda Gonzales in the TV4 soap opera Tre kronor, Anna in the 2007 drama film Daisy Diamond, Lisbeth Salander in the 2009 crime drama thriller films The Girl with the Dragon Tattoo, The Girl Who Played with Fire, and The Girl Who Kicked the Hornets' Nest, Leena in the 2010 drama film Beyond, Anna in the 2011 thriller film The Monitor, Madam Simza Heron in the 2011 period mystery action film Sherlock Holmes: Games of Shadows, Elizabeth Shaw in the 2012 science fiction horror film Prometheus and its 2017 sequel film Alien: Covenant, Beatrice in the 2013 action thriller film Dead Man Down, Nadia in the 2014 crime drama film The Drop, Raisa Demidova in the 2015 mystery thriller film Child 44, Alice Racine in the 2017 action thriller film Unlocked, Leila in the 2017 Netflix urban fantasy action film Bright, Monday, Tuesday, Wednesday, Thursday, Friday, Saturday, Sunday/Karen Settman in the 2017 Netflix dystopian science-fiction action thriller film What Happened to Monday, Bianca Lind in the 2018 crime comedy-drama film Stockholm, Sam Carlson in the 2019 Netflix action thriller film Close, Lizzie in the 2019 psychological thriller film Angel of Mine, Harriet Bauman in the Amazon Prime Video original political action thriller series Tom Clancy's Jack Ryan, Maja Reid in the 2020 thriller drama film The Secrets We Keep, Maria in the 2021 folk horror film Lamb, Lisa in the 2021 action comedy horror film The Trip, Bosilka in the 2022 horror dark fantasy drama film You Won't Be Alone, and Caroline Edh in the 2022 Netflix action thriller film Black Crab in a career that spans 1988–present. Her zodiac sign is Capricorn.

Noomi Rapace has been in 4 on-screen matchups, including Michael Nyqvist in The Girl Who Kicked the Hornet's Nest (2009), Colin Farrell in Dead Man Down (2013), Rachel McAdams in Passion (2012) and Tom Hardy in The Drop (2014).
